    "body": "> @ilmotta I think we shouldn't be compromising on the performance for some design details.\r\n\r\nFair point @OmarBasem, but I don't have the numbers to back up the claim that the performance is bad in general. I think we can all agree the performance is decent at this point. I can try to render the AC in a simpler screen without any blur effect, release it locally and see if I feel any difference. It'll give us a rough estimate if it's worth pursuing optimizations now, otherwise we might be optimizing just for the sake of optimizing without a noticeable difference.\r\n\r\n>To simulate the same blurry effect, we can have an Image background of one of the screens and on top of it the blurry view. That should give a very similar look.\r\n\r\nI thought about it before, it might be worth a shot since I'm not the only crazy ;)\r\n\r\n>If so, you can then easily just have the blurry view as the background of the screen.\r\n\r\nNice Omar, thanks for taking a look. The one thing to keep in mind is that `react-native-blur` is extremely buggy! It simply doesn't work as intended in many cases (I know that Parvesh and Javid also encountered many bugs). So yes, if we're lucky then it would be easy ;)\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nI'll take a deeper look, thanks for the analysis.\r\n\r\n",
