    "body": "@OmarBasem, I did a full investigation and experimentation around this issue.\r\n\r\nSo first off, the easiest part and probably the key factor here. Today `2023-02-08` there was a meeting with designers, @cammellos and @smohamedjavid, and @John-44 for a walkthrough on the new application settings, more specifically notification settings. Settings screens all use a true blurred background, just as the Activity Centre. \r\n\r\nThere was some discussion around the performance impact for users, but it was aligned that **we should use the solution that matches exactly what's in Figma**. Once we dogfood `status-mobile` and collect feedback around the experience, and if we feel like the performance is affecting the UX, then we can go back to the drawing board and see what we can do. We even have the option of getting help from external contributors specialized in ReactNative in case we need to build from scratch (low-level primitives) support for blurred stacked screens.\r\n\r\n----\r\n   \r\nNow for more technical stuff:\r\n\r\nI changed the Activity Centre to use a stacked screen, and the performance was **reduced** (from the user's perspective). There was a noticeable impact on the animation behavior because re-frame was rendering the notifications + the AC screen in the same batch. This behavior is largely unpredictable given the myriad of components on screen, but also expected and it's documented by re-frame. It's known that if some expensive components are rendered with lighter ones in the same batch, then the UI can become unresponsive. In practice, the animations to open the AC stopped working well, even after releasing for production (no emulation and compiler optimized). What I'm pointing out here is that replacing a modal screen won't automatically give better performance, as was clearly the case for the AC.\r\n\r\nBut there's a way to force re-frame to avoid rendering some components on the same batch, and if we do that judiciously, then the UI feels as snappy as it can get. The problem is that doing this is time consuming and requires workarounds. I did just that :nerd_face: to see where I'd get (it's in this [branch](https://github.com/status-im/status-mobile/compare/performance/render-activity-center-screen-without-popover?expand=1)) and I must say I'm very satisfied with the performance. The **caveat is that the screen can't blur the one below it**. The workaround if you want to know is: clean up the AC state (ugly...) when it's closed and fetch notifications only after a delay that allows the opening animation to run for around 150ms.\r\n\r\n----\r\n\r\nTherefore, after much consideration about possible solutions, including using fake blurred backgrounds (there are many downsides to this approach) and the new business requirements around blurred screens, I think we should consider the case closed until we dogfood more as John explained in the meeting.\r\n\r\nI'm closing this issue for now also because the performance is acceptable for our current needs. Thanks for bringing the topic to light. By no means it's the end of story ;)\r\n\r\n",
